AGI - They have come to the Gemelli despite the light, but almost constant, rain that from this morning falls on Rome. As every day, since Pope Francis is admitted, the faithful do not give up a moment of prayer for him under the statue of Wojtyla, where they also continue to leave small gifts and messages.
&nbsp;
"I always stop to pray, for him and for all those who suffer - says Ilaria, operator who works in this Polyclinic - Bergoglio must be strong. The thing that most saddens me is the suffering, that no one should suffer," he adds, while he fixes at the foot of the statue a rosary and a pink butterfly that made crochet.
&nbsp;
In the square of the Gemelli there are also families with children who stop for a few minutes: a child, kneeling, leaves a flyer with Sunday meditation, some ladies, alone or in small groups, pray with the rosary in hand. Among them is the young Rochelle, native to the Philippines: "I come from a distant country, but working in Rome is for me an opportunity of spiritual growth. Today I came here to recite the rosary for the Pope: I am very excited to be so close to him, what I can do is pray for his healing."
&nbsp;
Sister Emma and Sister Gilse - who are part of the Opera Don Orione, Congregation of the Little Missionary Sisters of Charity - stopped to pray in the chapel of the hospital: they came to participate in the Mass that every day is celebrated here from last Monday for the Pontiff. Today, however, the day of the Jubilee of the Political Foundation Gemelli, the function took place in San Pietro, with the homily of Monsignor Claudio Giuliodori, general ecclesiastical assistant of the Catholic University of the Sacred Heart.
&nbsp;
"We are here to pray for Pope Francis, we know that he is an elderly person and has health problems, we wish that he is still among us," the two religious say. Sister Emma, in particular, is Argentine: lives in Buenos Aires and is in Rome for a short time. "I met Bergoglio - he said - he was our bishop in Argentina, he often came to us for celebrations, or to find elderly and sick nuns." Fabio and Roberta arrive from Perugia: "We hope well, we hope that St. John will help Francis. We're only here to pray for him." They also had the opportunity to meet once the Pope: "in San Damaso for a private visit with some Ukrainian boys we had the opportunity to see him and say hello," they recall.
&nbsp;
Among the faithful are Anna and Filomena, from Nola to Rome for a specialization course, which took advantage of a break of the lessons for a quick passage to the Gemini: "Papa Francesco is a beautiful, simple person who knows how to communicate. Ours is a prayer of hope for him." Among the drawings and messages - many left in recent days by pupils of various schools of Rome and province - today there is also a small bronze statue depicting Wojtyla: "is the prototype of that then realized and placed in Chiavari - tells a man - I am a funder and I wanted to expose it here as a tribute. I would love to make one for Pope Bergoglio and give him a gift." &nbsp;

