&nbsp;
bronchospasm consists of a sudden restriction of bronchi, with passage of air in the lungs which is reduced and with a consequent difficulty in breathing. It is bronchospasm when the smooth muscles of bronchi, which surround the airways of the lungs, contract abnormally and excessively. Hence a restriction of bronchi, which causes less air inflow within the lungs, with relative difficulty breathing for the patient.
&nbsp;
You can have sibilant breathing or rant, dry or fat cough, dispnea, sense of constriction. It can be solved in a few minutes also with the use of bronchodilators, and in case of accidental ingestion for example of vomiting, as in the case of the Pope, bronchoasuction is performed. bronchospasm can be triggered by multiple factors, especially by inflammatory diseases such as as asthma (of which the Pope suffers), bronchitis, and of course pneumonia.
&nbsp;
When the saturation of the blood, i.e. the amount of oxygen, drops drastically, as evidently happened to the Pope this afternoon, the "naselli" are no longer enough, that is, the nasal cannules that administer oxygen. Doctors inform you that they are recourse to a non-invasive mechanical ventilation at positive pressure, which is replaced by the patient in the various stages of respiratory acts; can be nasal, facial, total-face or scafandro, depending on the needs and tolerability.
&nbsp;
If correctly applied, it reduces tracheal gold intoxication and the need for tracheostomy. It is divided into two techniques: Continuous ventilation at positive pressure and positive airway pressure at two levels. In the positive continuous pressure of airways, the pressure is maintained constant throughout the respiratory cycle without any additional inspiratory support. With the positive pressure of airways at two levels, the doctor sets both positive airway pressure and inspiratory pressure and respiratory acts are stimulated by the patient.

